    <section class="uv-materials-section">
        <h2>UV Light Control & Materials</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">Advanced materials manipulate ultraviolet (UV) light through various mechanisms, including absorption, reflection, fluorescence, and complex interactions facilitated by nanostructures and specialized material compositions.</p>
        
        <div class="materials-table">
            <div class="table-header">
                <div class="header-cell">Material Type</div>
                <div class="header-cell">Mechanism</div>
                <div class="header-cell">Applications</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">AlGaN-based semiconductors</div>
                <div class="cell">Light Emission (LEDs)</div>
                <div class="cell">Deep UV (DUV) light sources for sterilization and bio/medical uses</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">Nanostructured solids (etched silica)</div>
                <div class="cell">Diffraction/Polarization control</div>
                <div class="cell">Extreme UV (EUV) light generation, probing computer chips and biological cells</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">UV Fused Silica, CaF₂, Sapphire</div>
                <div class="cell">Transmission</div>
                <div class="cell">UV optics, lenses, and filters due to high transparency in UV range</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">Inorganic filters (TiO₂, ZnO)</div>
                <div class="cell">Reflection/Scattering</div>
                <div class="cell">Sunscreen creams and UV-protective coatings</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">Organic absorbers (Avobenzone, Oxybenzone)</div>
                <div class="cell">Absorption (photoisomerization)</div>
                <div class="cell">Sunscreens, fabrics, and personal care products</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">Fluorescent materials & phosphors</div>
                <div class="cell">Absorption/Re-emission (as visible light)</div>
                <div class="cell">Fluorescent lamps, art conservation, security features</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">Aluminum (Al)</div>
                <div class="cell">High reflectivity</div>
                <div class="cell">UV reflecting materials in specialized optical systems</div>
            </div>
            <div class="table-row">
                <div class="cell">Photoinitiators/Polymers</div>
                <div class="cell">Photochemistry (curing/cross-linking)</div>
                <div class="cell">UV-curable resins/coatings for manufacturing and batteries</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="applications-section">
    <!-- Automatically search recent advances & update the section regularly -->
        <h2>Recent Advances & Applications</h2>
        <div class="applications-grid">
            <div class="application-card">
                <h3>Extreme UV Lithography</h3>
                <p>Specialized materials, including highly reflective optics and tin droplet plasmas, are used in advanced machinery to generate and focus extreme ultraviolet (EUV) light for manufacturing advanced microprocessors.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="application-card">
                <h3>Deep UV LEDs</h3>
                <p>Research focuses on improving the efficiency of Aluminum Gallium Nitride (AlGaN) based LEDs for use in compact, high-efficiency sterilization and medical devices.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="application-card">
                <h3>Nanoscale Control</h3>
                <p>Scientists have developed methods using nanostructured solid materials, such as etched silica gratings, to control properties of generated EUV light like polarization and direction.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="application-card">
                <h3>Biomimetic Materials</h3>
                <p>Development of nature-based UV-shielding materials, such as those made from lignin and melanin, offers eco-friendly alternatives for food packaging and sunscreen fabrics.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="application-card">
                <h3>Intelligent Light Manipulation</h3>
                <p>Novel stimulus-responsive materials are being developed for applications in energy-saving smart windows and agricultural films with dynamic UV and visible light control.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="application-card">
                <h3>Key Research</h3>
                <p><a href="https://ir.arcnl.nl/pub/521/2025-PhD-Thesis-Dion-Engels.pdf" target="_blank">Solid-State Laser-Driven Vaporization and Ionization of Tin →</a></p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="challenges-section">
        <h2>DUV LED Efficiency Challenges</h2>
        <div class="challenges-grid">
            <div class="challenge-card">
                <h4>Material Quality & Defect Density</h4>
                <p><strong>Issue:</strong> AlGaN layers grown on sapphire substrates suffer from large lattice mismatch, resulting in high threading dislocation densities (10¹⁰ cm⁻²).</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Acts as non-radiative recombination centers, significantly reducing internal quantum efficiency (IQE).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="challenge-card">
                <h4>Inefficient Doping & Carrier Injection</h4>
                <p><strong>Issue:</strong> Achieving high conductivity in both n-type and p-type AlGaN layers is difficult due to magnesium (Mg) activation energy increasing dramatically with higher Al content.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Poor carrier injection efficiency (CIE) and high operating voltages.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="challenge-card">
                <h4>Low Light Extraction Efficiency</h4>
                <p><strong>Issue:</strong> p-GaN contact layers strongly absorb DUV light, and emitted light tends to be polarized in TM mode, easily trapped by total internal reflection.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Much of generated light is lost before exiting the chip.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="challenge-card">
                <h4>Thermal Management & Reliability</h4>
                <p><strong>Issue:</strong> Low electrical conductivity of AlGaN and non-radiative recombination processes generate significant heat. Sapphire substrates have low thermal conductivity.</p>
                <p><strong>Impact:</strong> Increased junction temperature accelerates device degradation and shortens lifespan.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>
</div>

